On 12/06/2010 07:14 PM, Gordon Mohr wrote:
&gt; The &#39;NotExceedsDocumentLengthTresholdDecideRule&#39; [sic] applies its
&gt; configured decision if the document length does NOT exceed the given
&gt; threshold.
&gt;
&gt; Your threshold is 10. Almost every document will actually EXCEED that
&gt; threshold, so this rule does not apply.
&gt;
&gt; You may want to use &#39;ExceedsDocumentLengthThresholdDecideRule&#39; instead,
&gt; to REJECT all documents that do exceed the threshold.
&gt;
&gt; I also suggest always using a DecideRuleSequence with a
&gt; constant-decision rule (AcceptDecideRule, RejectDecideRule) in the first
&gt; position to set a clear default, starting decision if no later rules
&gt; act. (Otherwise, if no rules act, the standing decision will be NONE,
&gt; which confusingly means different things in scoping vs.
&gt; processor-application.)
&gt;
&gt; If following this rule-of-thumb, you could achieve your goal in two
&gt; different ways:
&gt;
&gt; DecideRuleSequence
&gt;    AcceptDecideRule
&gt;    ExceedsDocumentLengthThresholdDecideRule(REJECT,threshold=1048576)
&gt;
&gt; ...or...
&gt;
&gt; DecideRuleSequence
&gt;    RejectDecideRule
&gt;    NotExceedsDocumentLengthTresholdDecideRule(ACCEPT,threshold=1048576)
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;m going to rename these for less confusion (and to get rid of the
&gt; spelling error in &#39;Treshold&#39;) in the next release. I propose:
&gt;
&gt;    DocumentLongerThanDecideRule -- above a threshold
&gt;    DocumentNoLongerThanDecideRule -- up to (inclusive of) a threshold
&gt;
&gt; Are those clearer or are there any other suggestions?
&gt;
&gt; - Gordon @ IA
